<LP>
   GM AND FORD POSTED sharply lower second-quarter earnings,
reflecting hard times in the U.S. market and economic unrest
in Brazil. Ford's profit tumbled 45% while GM reported a 38%
decline. The remainder of the year could be difficult, too,
amid weak demand in the U.S. and competition from Japan.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A former Drexel official, Peter Ackerman, has become the
subject of a new government probe into possible price
manipulation, according to people familiar with the
investigation. Mr. Ackerman was once top deputy to ex-junk
bond king Michael Milken.
   ---
   A plan to propose higher taxes on alcoholic beverages and
limits on deductions for state and local taxes was
tentatively agreed to by the administration and congressional
Republicans, according to people close to the plan. But
support was shaky.
   ---
   OPEC ministers neared agreement on a new production
ceiling intended to reduce the current world oil glut and
push up crude oil prices.
   ---
   Growing real estate problems in California are hurting
lenders. Coast Savings Financial reported a $28.7 million
second-quarter loss, following losses by CalFed and HomeFed.
   ---
   GE was ordered to pay a $10 million criminal fine and
agreed to pay $20 million in civil penalties in connection
with fraudulent defense contract billings to the U.S. Army.
   ---
   Sallie Mae has proposed taking over the portfolio of a
troubled student-loan guarantor, a move that would greatly
expand its influence in the education financing field.
   ---
   House and Senate conferees agreed on comprehensive
oil-spill legislation that would end a 16-year congressional
stalemate on the issue.
   ---
   Cigarette package warnings don't protect tobacco makers
from product liability lawsuits, New Jersey's Supreme Court
ruled. The decision opens the door for a review of the issue
by the U.S. Supreme Court.
   ---
   A House panel voted to reimpose rate regulation on basic
cable-TV service. The measure also would benefit fledgling
competitors of cable.
   ---
   UAL's profit rose slightly in the second quarter, aided by
the sale of aircraft. But Midway Airlines recorded a hefty
loss for the period.
   ---
   Westinghouse agreed to acquire Knoll International,
doubling the size of its office-furniture business.
   ---
   Eli Lilly was named in a second lawsuit charging that its
popular new antidepressant drug Prozac can cause violent and
destructive behavior. Lilly's stock fell $4.375 to $79.625.
   ---
   The Senate embraced a proposal to revamp the federal
crop-insurance program and cover its underwriting losses,
putting senators at odds with the House's intention to
scuttle the long-troubled program.
   ---
   Microsoft is planning a costly campaign to win a bigger
piece of the market for software that ties together personal
computers. The effort will cost the company up to $50
million.
   ---
   Continental Bank moved closer to full private ownership as
the FDIC approved plans to sell a 26% stake in the Chicago
banking concern.
